<h2 id=3D"LocalizationL10n-Introduction">Introduction</h2>
<p>DSpace ships with a number of interface translations. This page provides=
 information on areas that can be localized by means of configuration or cu=
stomization. By default, DSpace will look at the user's browser language. I=
f it has a language file in the user's language, it will render the interfa=
ce in that language. If not, it will default to English or another default =
that you have configured.</p>
<h2 id=3D"LocalizationL10n-Commonareasoflocalization">Common areas of local=
ization</h2>
<h3 id=3D"LocalizationL10n-Enablingadditionallocales"><span>Enabling additi=
onal locales</span></h3>
<p>Out of the box, DSpace only has English enabled as a supported locale. A=
dditional locales and the default locale are managed through the following =
parameters in dspace.cfg:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px=
;">
<b>dspace.cfg configuration parameters</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"theme: Confluence; brush: java; gutter: false" style=3D"font-=
size:12px;">webui.supported.locales
default.locale</pre>=20
</div>
</div>
<p>You can change default.locale to a different one than English&nbsp;<stro=
ng>after</strong> adding it to webui.supported.locales.</p>
<h3 id=3D"LocalizationL10n-Localizationofemailmessages"><span style=3D"line=
-height: 1.5625;">Localization of email messages</span></h3>
<p>All email templates used by DSpace can be found in</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px=
;">
<b>Path to the DSpace email templates</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"theme: Confluence; brush: java; gutter: false" style=3D"font-=
size:12px;"> [dspace]/config/emails</pre>=20
</div>
</div>
<p>The contents of the emails can be edited and translated.&nbsp;</p>
<h3 id=3D"LocalizationL10n-Metadatalocalization">Metadata localization</h3>
<p>DSpace associates each metadata field value with a language code (though=
 it may be left empty, e.g. for numeric values).</p>
<h2 id=3D"LocalizationL10n-XMLUIspecificlocalization">XMLUI specific locali=
zation</h2>
<h3 id=3D"LocalizationL10n-Messagecatalog">Message catalog</h3>
<p>XMLUI supports multiple languages through the use of internationalizatio=
n catalogues as defined by the&nbsp;<a href=3D"http://cocoon.apache.org/2.1=
/userdocs/i18nTransformer.html" title=3D"Cocoon Internationalization Transf=
ormer" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">Cocoon Internationalization=
 Transformer</a>. Each catalog contains the translation of all user-display=
ed strings into a particular language or variant. Each catalog is a single =
xml file whose name is based upon the language it is designated for, thus:<=
/p>
<p>messages_<em>language</em>_<em>country</em>_<em>variant</em>.xml</p>
<p>messages_<em>language</em>_<em>country</em>.xml</p>
<p>messages_<em>language</em>.xml</p>
<p>messages.xml</p>
<p>The interface will automatically determine which file to select based up=
on the user's browser and system configuration. For example, if the user's =
browser is set to Australian English then first the system will check if&nb=
sp;<em>messages_en_au.xml</em>&nbsp;is available. If this translation is no=
t available it will fall back to&nbsp;<em>messages_en.xml</em>, and finally=
 if that is not available,&nbsp;<em>messages.xml</em>.</p>
<h3 id=3D"LocalizationL10n-Wheretofindthemessagecatalog">Where to find the =
message catalog</h3>
<p>The latest <strong>English</strong> message catalog is part of the main =
DSpace distribution and can be found at:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px=
;">
<b>Location of the XMLUI message catalog in the DSpace source tree</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"theme: Confluence; brush: java; gutter: false" style=3D"font-=
size:12px;">[dspace-source]/dspace-xmlui/src/main/webapp/i18n/messages.xml<=
/pre>=20
</div>
</div>
<p>The <strong>different translations</strong> for this message catalog are=
 being managed separately from the DSpace core project, in order to release=
 updates for these files more frequently than the DSpace software itself. V=
isit the&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://github.com/DSpace/dspace-xmlui-lang" class=
=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">dspace-xmlui-lang project on Github</a>=
.</p>
<h3 id=3D"LocalizationL10n-Wheretoedit">Where to edit</h3>
<p>In some cases you may want to add additional keys to the message catalog=
 or changing the particular wording of DSpace concepts. For example, you ma=
y want to change &quot;Communities&quot; into &quot;Departments&quot;. Thes=
e kind of changes may get automatically overwritten again when you upgrade =
to the newest version of DSpace. It is therefore advised to keep such chang=
es isolated in the following location:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px=
;">
<b>Recommended location for i18n customizations</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"theme: Confluence; brush: java; gutter: false" style=3D"font-=
size:12px;">[dspace-source]/dspace/modules/xmlui/src/main/webapp/i18n/</pre=
>=20
</div>
</div>
<p>After rebuilding DSpace, any messages files placed in this directory wil=
l be automatically included in the XMLUI web application. Files of the same=
 name will override any default files. By default, this full directory path=
 may not exist or may be empty. If it does not exist, you can simply create=
 it. You can place any number of translation catalogues in this directory. =
To add additional translations, just add another copy of the&nbsp;<em>messa=
ges.xml</em>&nbsp;file translated into the specific language and country va=
riant you need.&nbsp;</p>
<p>After building and deploying, DSpace will finally read the files from th=
e following location:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px=
;">
<b>Location where your i18n files are being deployed</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"theme: Confluence; brush: java; gutter: false" style=3D"font-=
size:12px;">[dspace]/webapps/xmlui/i18n/messages.xml</pre>=20
</div>
</div>
<p><em>Again, note that you will need to rebuild DSpace for these changes t=
o take effect in your installed XMLUI web application!</em></p>=20
<div class=3D"aui-message problem shadowed information-macro">=20
<p class=3D"title">Do not customize your messages in the webapps directory<=
/p>=20
<span class=3D"aui-icon icon-problem">Icon</span>=20
<div class=3D"message-content">=20
<p>While it seems like a fast option to change your messages straight in th=
e deployed dspace directory, these changes are very volatile. If you rebuil=
d and redeploy DSpace, these changes will get lost.</p>=20
</div>=20
</div>=20
<p>For more information about the&nbsp;<code style=3D"line-height: 1.428571=
5;">[dspace-source]/dspace/modules/</code>&nbsp;directory, and how it may b=
e used to &quot;overlay&quot; (or customize) the default XMLUI interface, c=
lasses and files, please see:&nbsp;<a href=3D"/display/DSDOC4x/Advanced+Cus=
tomisation">Advanced Customisation</a></p>
<h3 id=3D"LocalizationL10n-DifferencewithJSPUI">Difference with JSPUI</h3>
<p>In JSPUI, a wider range of files, including input-forms.xml and default.=
license can be localized by adding _COUNTRY at the end of the filename. Thi=
s is currently not supported in XMLUI.</p>
<h2 id=3D"LocalizationL10n-JSPUIspecificlocalization">JSPUI specific locali=
zation</h2>
<div>
<h3 id=3D"LocalizationL10n-Messagecatalog.1">Message catalog</h3>
<p>The&nbsp;<a href=3D"http://jakarta.apache.org/taglibs/doc/standard-1.0-d=
oc/intro.html" title=3D"Java Standard Tag Library v1.0" class=3D"external-l=
ink" rel=3D"nofollow">Java Standard Tag Library v1.0</a>&nbsp;is used to sp=
ecify messages in the JSPs like this:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"theme: Confluence; brush: java; gutter: false" style=3D"font-=
size:12px;">&lt;H1&gt;&lt;fmt:message key=3D&quot;jsp.search.results.title&=
quot;/&gt;&lt;/H1&gt;</pre>=20
</div>
</div>
<p>This message can be changed using the&nbsp;<em>config/language-packs/Mes=
sages.properties</em>&nbsp;file. This must be done at build-time:&nbsp;<em>=
Messages.properties</em>&nbsp;is placed in the&nbsp;<em>dspace.war</em>&nbs=
p;Web application file.</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"theme: Confluence; brush: java; gutter: false" style=3D"font-=
size:12px;">jsp.search.results.title =3D Search Results</pre>=20
</div>
</div>
<p>Phrases may have parameters to be passed in, to make the job of translat=
ing easier, reduce the number of 'keys' and to allow translators to make th=
e translated text flow more appropriately for the target language. Here is =
an example of a phrase in which two parameters are passed in:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"theme: Confluence; brush: java; gutter: false" style=3D"font-=
size:12px;">jsp.search.results.text =3D Results {0}-{1} of {2} </pre>=20
</div>
</div>
<p>Multiple&nbsp;<em style=3D"line-height: 1.4285715;">Messages.properties<=
/em>&nbsp;can be created for different languages. See&nbsp;<a href=3D"http:=
//java.sun.com/j2se/1.4.2/docs/api/java/util/ResourceBundle.html#getBundle(=
java.lang.String,%20java.util.Locale,%20java.lang.ClassLoader)" style=3D"li=
ne-height: 1.4285715;" title=3D"ResourceBundle.getBundle" class=3D"external=
-link" rel=3D"nofollow">ResourceBundle.getBundle</a>. e.g. you can add Germ=
an and Canadian French translations:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"theme: Confluence; brush: java; gutter: false" style=3D"font-=
size:12px;">Messages_de.properties
Messages_fr_CA.properties</pre>=20
</div>
</div>
<p>The end user's browser settings determine which language is used by defa=
ult. The user can change the language by clicking a link in the UI. These l=
inks are visible if more than one language is configured in DSpace. The Eng=
lish language file&nbsp;<em>Messages.properties</em>&nbsp;(or the default s=
erver locale) will be used as a fallback if there's no language bundle for =
the end user's preferred language. Note that the English file is not called=
&nbsp;<em>Messages_en.properties. </em>This is because it is always availab=
le as a fallback, regardless of server configuration.</p>
<h3 id=3D"LocalizationL10n-Wheretofindthemessagecatalog.1">Where to find th=
e message catalog</h3>
<p>The latest&nbsp;<strong>English</strong>&nbsp;message catalog is part of=
 the main DSpace distribution and can be found at:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px=
;">
<b>Location of the JSPUI message catalog in the DSpace source tree</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"theme: Confluence; brush: java; gutter: false" style=3D"font-=
size:12px;">[dspace-source]/dspace-api/src/main/resources/Messages.properti=
es</pre>=20
</div>
</div>
<p>The&nbsp;<strong>different translations</strong>&nbsp;for this message c=
atalog are being managed separately from the DSpace core project, in order =
to release updates for these files more frequently than the DSpace software=
 itself.&nbsp;Visit the&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://github.com/DSpace/dspace-ap=
i-lang" class=3D"external-link" rel=3D"nofollow">dspace-api-lang project on=
 Github</a>.</p>
<h3 id=3D"LocalizationL10n-Wheretoedit.1">Where to edit</h3>
<p>In some cases you may want to add additional keys to the message catalog=
 or changing the particular wording of DSpace concepts. For example, you ma=
y want to change &quot;Communities&quot; into &quot;Departments&quot;. Thes=
e kind of changes may get automatically overwritten again when you upgrade =
to the newest version of DSpace. It is therefore advised to keep such chang=
es isolated in the following location:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl" style=3D"border-bottom-width: 1px=
;">
<b>Recommended location for i18n customizations</b>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl">=20
<pre class=3D"theme: Confluence; brush: java; gutter: false" style=3D"font-=
size:12px;">[dspace-source]/dspace/modules/jspui/src/main/resources/</pre>=
=20
</div>
</div>
<p>After rebuilding DSpace, any messages files placed in this directory wil=
l be automatically included in the JSPUI web application. Files of the same=
 name will override any default files. By default, this full directory path=
 may not exist or may be empty. If it does not exist, you can simply create=
 it. You can place any number of translation catalogues in this directory. =
To add additional translations, just add another copy of the M<em>essages.p=
roperties</em>&nbsp;file translated into the specific language and country =
variant you need.&nbsp;</p>
<p>After building and deploying, DSpace will finally read the files from th=
e dspace-api-4.0.jar file in your&nbsp;<span style=3D"color: rgb(34,34,34);=
">[tomcat]\webapps\jspui\WEB-INF\lib directory.</span></p>
<p><em>Again, note that you will need to rebuild DSpace for these changes t=
o take effect in your installed JSPUI web application!</em></p>
<p>For more information about the&nbsp;<code>[dspace-source]/dspace/modules=
/</code>&nbsp;directory, and how it may be used to &quot;overlay&quot; (or =
customize) the default XMLUI interface, classes and files, please see:&nbsp=
;<a href=3D"/display/DSDOC4x/Advanced+Customisation">Advanced Customisation=
</a></p>
<h3 id=3D"LocalizationL10n-Localizationofinput-forms.xmlandlicense.default"=
>Localization of input-forms.xml and license.default</h3>
<p>The display labels for input-forms.xml and the text in the default submi=
ssion license (license.default) are currently not managed in the messages c=
atalogs. To localize these files, you can create versions of these files in=
 the same folders, appending _COUNTRY at the end of the filename, before th=
e extension. For example, input-forms_de.xml can be used to translate the s=
ubmission form labels in German.</p>
</div>
